{{hatnote|extraclasses=plainlinks|1=This is a [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Lists#Incomplete lists|dynamic list]] in which entries can be added. You can help by [{{fullurl:{{FULLPAGENAME}}|action=edit}} expanding it] with [[Wikipedia:Reliable sources|reliably sourced]] entries that were longer walks, runs or wheelchair expeditions than the shortest ones listed.}}

This is a list of the '''longest walks''' that have occurred in groups and on solo or duo projects. Many have promoted social causes or medical conditions. Some have been done mostly for the experience.

Groups consist of three or more people who walked at least most of the entire distance. Solo/duo walks are one or two people. The difference is that the former is tougher to organise logistically, especially when crossing international borders, since there generally needs to be greater accommodations and more thorough approvals for a group. There is also a tougher process of decision making with even a small group than with one or two people. Some people walking in groups say that the walking part can be easier than dealing with group politics and dynamics.

The walks should be continuous, save for a few weeks to organise through other countries. There is a separate section for long runs and wheelchair expeditions that were not walks.

== Longest group walks ==
These were walks involving three or more long-distance participants.

=== A Walk of the People – A Pilgrimage for Life ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|7,000|mi}}
* '''Date:''' March 1984-November 1985
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|368|mi}}
* '''Details:''' A [[Walk of the People – A Pilgrimage for Life]] called for an end to the [[Cold War]] with better relations between the U.S. and former [[Soviet Union]]. Walkers started at [[Point Conception]], California, and went through Texas and the Deep South to [[New York City]]. A core group of eight flew to [[Dublin]], Ireland, and walked to the border of the former [[East Germany]]. They obtained visas to [[People's Republic of Hungary|Hungary]] and walked to that border before visiting several cities by train. Some walked to [[Geneva]], Switzerland, then organised a trip to [[Moscow]], Soviet Union, by train. The project attracted a wide range of support from across the political spectrum and was covered in the media by hundreds of newspapers and radio and television stations in those countries. It was the only walk from the U.S. to Moscow that went through the Deep South, Northern Ireland, and Hungary, so that added to the mileage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/7ba3f8625c2931f93edb4a112db1c95e|title=U.S. Peace Activists Denied East German Visas - Associated Press|date=September 12, 1985|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>

=== Bethlehem Peace Pilgrimage ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|6,500|mi}}
* '''Date:''' April 1982-December 1983
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|342|mi}}
* '''Details:''' This [[peace walk]] of about 20 core people started from [[Seattle]] and walked across the U.S. to [[Washington, D.C.]] Members then flew to [[Ireland]] and walked through much of Europe, taking a boat from [[Greece]] to the [[Middle East]]. The project ended in [[Bethlehem]] in the [[West Bank]]. It was led by Jesuit Fr. [[Jack Morris (Jesuit)|Jack Morris]] and Fr. [[George Zabelka]], the pastor for the airmen who dropped the atomic bombs on Japan in 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2012/aug/31/shawn-vestal-a-pilgrimage-and-a-life-pursuing|title=A pilgrimage, and a life, pursuing peace|publisher=The Spokane Spokesman-Review, Aug. 31, 2012|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>

=== San Francisco to Moscow Walk for Peace ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|5,900|mi}}
* '''Date:''' December 1960-October 1961
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|590|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Organised by the [[Committee for Non-Violent Action]], about ten core people started from San Francisco and walked to New York in six months. More people joined in Europe, and the project, led by pacifist leaders [[A.J. Muste]] and [[Bradford Lyttle]], covered about {{convert|5,900|mi}} in just ten months. Unlike numerous projects, they were able to walk through the Soviet Union, and the distance walked per month was significantly higher than most long group walks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/10/04/archives/peace-marchers-reach-red-square-but-soviet-prohibits-speeches-peace.html|title=Peace Marchers Reach Red Square but Soviet Prohibits Speeches|publisher=UPI|date=October 4, 1961|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The San Francisco to Moscow Walk for Peace|author=Bradford Lyttle|publisher=Midwest Pacifist Commentator|date=September 23, 1987}}</ref>

===A Walk to Moscow===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|5,500|mi}}
* '''Date:''' March 1981-October 1983
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|275|mi}}
* '''Details:''' This [[peace walk]] started from [[Bangor, Washington]] to [[Boston]]. Members continued in the United Kingdom, walking to the border of the former [[East Germany]]. Some stayed in a village for nine months to negotiate for visas to walk in [[Czechoslovakia]] and [[Poland]]. Some then traveled to cities in the Soviet Union by train and tried to walk to Moscow but were stopped and sent back to Minsk.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ecommons.cornell.edu/handle/1813/25047 |title=Peace walk is subject of talk|newspaper=Cornell Chronicle|date=February 17, 1983|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

===World Peace Walk===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|5,500|mi}}
* '''Date:''' April 1982-August 1984
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|190|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Led by writer and activist [[C.B. Hall]], participants walked from Seattle to New York and then across much of Europe. They were not allowed to walk in Eastern Europe but obtained visas to camp and meet people in East Germany for a few days. Some visited Moscow to meet with Soviet Peace Committee officials. <ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/Library/peace/DG151-175/DG162walkabout.htm|title=Walkabout Peace and Justice Records, 1981-1992|author=C.B. Hall|publisher=Walkabout Peace and Justice|accessdate=September 21, 2020}}</ref>

=== A Walk of the People – A Pilgrimage for Life ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|7,000|mi}}
* '''Date:''' March 1984-November 1985
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|368|mi}}
* '''Details:''' A [[Walk of the People – A Pilgrimage for Life]] called for an end to the [[Cold War]] with better relations between the U.S. and former [[Soviet Union]]. Walkers started at [[Point Conception]], California, and went through Texas and the Deep South to [[New York City]]. A core group of eight flew to [[Dublin]], Ireland, and walked to the border of the former [[East Germany]]. They obtained visas to [[People's Republic of Hungary|Hungary]] and walked to that border before visiting several cities by train. Some walked to [[Geneva]], Switzerland, then organised a trip to [[Moscow]], Soviet Union, by train. The project attracted a wide range of support from across the political spectrum and was covered in the media by hundreds of newspapers and radio and television stations in those countries. It was the only walk from the U.S. to Moscow that went through the Deep South, Northern Ireland, and Hungary, so that added to the mileage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/7ba3f8625c2931f93edb4a112db1c95e|title=U.S. Peace Activists Denied East German Visas - Associated Press|date=September 12, 1985|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>

=== HikaNation ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|4,286|mi}}
* '''Date:''' April 1980-May 1981
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|330|mi}}
* '''Details:''' HikaNation was a 14-month cross-country backpacking trip starting at [[Golden Gate Park]] in [[San Francisco]], California on April 12, 1980, and ending at [[Cape Henlopen]], Delaware on May 27, 1981 after traversing over 4,286 miles and passing through 14 states and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hikanation.com|title=HikaNation|access-date=2020-12-15}}</ref>

===Interfaith Pilgrimage for Peace and Life===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|3,100|mi}}
* '''Date:''' December 1994-August 1995
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|388|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Led by [[Nipponzan-Myōhōji-Daisanga]] Japanese Buddhist monks, this walk started in [[Auschwitz]], Poland, and ended in [[Nagasaki]], Japan. More than 1,000 people from different nations joined at various times along the route that passed through war zones in [[Bosnia]], as well as troubled parts of [[Israel]], the [[West Bank]], [[Jordan]], [[Iraq]], [[Cambodia]], [[Vietnam]] and the [[Philippines]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://teeksaphoto.org/Archive/Exhibits/95PilgrF/AshesLightPDFs/00Cover_Contents_Foreword.pdf|title=Ashes and Light: Interfaith Pilgrimage for Peace and Life|publisher=Nipponzan Myohoji, 1996|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

===Great March for Climate Action===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|3,100|mi}}
* '''Date:''' March 2014-November 2014
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|388|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Led by former Iowa state representative [[Ed Fallon]], the [[Great March for Climate Action]] called attention to the need for a more substantive response to climate change. About 30 people hiked most of the distance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/2014/10/20/climate-march/17603915/|title=Climate marchers have sore feet, but feel good about work|date=October 20, 2014|newspaper=Des Moines Register|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== The Longest Walk ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|3,000|mi}}
* '''Date:''' February 1978-July 1978
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|600|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Several hundred Native Americans and supporters marched from [[Alcatraz Island]] in San Francisco to Washington, D.C., to affirm American Indians’ land and water rights. Some elders and organisers camped on the [[National Mall]] to end the [[Longest Walk]]. Similar projects were organised in 1980, 1984, 2008, 2011, 2013 and 2016.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.newamericanjournal.net/2018/09/longest-walk-peace-pole-returns-to-washington-and-greenbelt-national-park|title=Native American Longest Walk History Remembered in Washington and Greenbelt National Park|author=Glynn Wilson|publisher=New American Journal|date=September 7, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.recorder.com/my-turn-carlson-ChangetheSystemNottheClimate-29004984|title=Change the system, not the climate|author= Suzanne Carlson|newspaper=Greenfield Recorder|date=October 7, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== United Souls of Awareness Walk ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|3,000|mi}}
* '''Date:''' April 2006-April 2007
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|267|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Four musicians/artists in their 20s walked from [[Venice Beach, California]] to New York to encourage creative pursuits.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sharonherald.com/news/local_news/a-trek-of-peace-many-colors-creative-quartet-traveling-from/article_eddb8722-2d13-5275-b482-59803c564d68.html|title=A trek of peace, many colors: Creative quartet traveling from coast to coast|first=Tom|last=Davidson|date=February 19, 2007|publisher=Sharon (Pa.) Herald|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== [[Alexander Gabyshev]]'s Walk===

* '''Length:''' {{convert|2,000|mi}} [forced to stop by authorities]
* '''Date:''' March 2019-May 2020
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|133|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Gabyshev, a shaman, started walking from the Republic of [[Sakha]] in far east Russia with the goal of reaching Moscow some {{convert|5,000|mi}} later and performing a ritual to cause President [[Vladimir Putin]] to resign. He was joined by two other core walkers, and as many as 1,000 people greeted him during the first almost {{convert|2,000|mi}}. In September 2019, Russian authorities detained him and sent him to a psychiatric hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/09/20/russia-sends-shaman-en-route-to-exorcise-putin-to-psychiatric-hospital-a67364|title=Russia Sends Shaman en Route to Exorcise Putin to Psychiatric Hospital|date=September 20, 2019|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> In early 2020, authorities stopped his walk for the third time. He was committed to a Russian mental asylum by a court order in May 2020, a move criticised by officials from [[Amnesty International]] and other organisations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/02/05/siberian-shaman-files-complaint-with-european-rights-court-a69175|title=Siberian Shaman Files Complaint With European Rights Court|date=February 5, 2020|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/06/02/anti-putin-shaman-forced-into-mental-asylum-in-siberia-a70460|title=Anti-Putin Shaman Forced Into Mental Asylum in Siberia|date=June 2, 2020|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=September 21, 2020}}</ref>

== Longest Solo or Duo Walks ==
These are walks done by one or two people. The length of some usually relates to the difficulties of securing access to walk in certain countries.

=== Jean Béliveau ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|46,600|mi}}
* '''Date:''' August 2000-October 2011
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|348|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Setting out from Montreal, the Canadian small business owner covered some {{convert|46,600|mi}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ibtimes.com/canadian-man-walks-around-world-11-years-324266 |title=Canadian Man Walks Around the World in 11 Years|author= Mark Johanson|newspaper=International Business Times|date=October 18, 2011|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> and wore out 49 pairs of shoes while walking through 64 countries. He met four Nobel Peace Prize winners, including [[Nelson Mandela]] in South Africa. His walk raised awareness for children who suffer from violence, with the start of the project coinciding with a similarly themed [[United Nations]] initiative. He pushed a three-wheeled stroller carrying food and supplies such as a tent and returned to Montreal to a welcome of several hundred people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/jean-b%C3%A9liveau-s-11-years-on-the-road-1.1070673 |title= Jean Béliveau's 11 years on the road|author= Jon Hembrey|publisher= CBC News|date=February 7, 2011|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>

=== Peace Pilgrim ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|43,500|mi}} 
* '''Date:''' January 1953-July 1981
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|128|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Citing the need for a pilgrim to make a strong statement against militarism during the Korean War, Mildred Norman changed her name to [[Peace Pilgrim]] in 1953 and walked continuously back and forth across the U.S. She kept walking until her death in 1981, ironically in a car accident after she accepted a ride to a speaking engagement. She stopped counting miles after reaching {{convert|25,000|mi}} but estimated she covered {{convert|1,500|mi}} per sneakers and wore out 29 pairs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/01/01/168346591/peace-pilgrims-28-year-walk-for-a-meaningful-way-of-life |title= Peace Pilgrim's 28-Year Walk For 'A Meaningful Way of Life'|author=Zak Rosen|publisher=NPR|date=January 1, 2013|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://laterbloomer.com/peace-pilgrim |title= Peace Pilgrim's 28-Year Walk for 'A Meaningful Way of Life'|author=Debra Eve|publisher=Later Bloomer|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>

=== Ignacio Dean Mouliaá ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|20,505|mi}}
* '''Date:''' March 2013-March 2016
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|570|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Nicknamed “Nacho Dean,” Mouliaá walked across several continents to raise awareness for environmental causes. Leaving his native Spain, he traveled through 31 countries, pushing some food and supplies on a trekking tricycle. He survived violent attacks in Mexico, Peru and El Salvador, as well as a dog bite in Honduras.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.typicallyspanish.com/news-spain/national/A_Spaniard_has_spent_three_years_walking_around_the_world_to_document_climate_change.shtml|title=A Spaniard has spent three years walking around the world to document climate change|publisher=Typically Spanish|date=March 21, 2016|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/local/features/2015/12/24/walking-around-the-world/77833182|title=Man walking around the world - for real|author= Gary Shapiro|newspaper=USA Today|date=December 24, 2015|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>

=== George Meegan ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|19,019|mi}}
* '''Date:''' January 1977-September 1983
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|238|mi}}
* '''Details:''' [[George Meegan]], a British adventurer and former [[Merchant Navy]] seaman, hiked across two continents, from the southern tip of [[South America]] at [[Tierra Del Fuego]] to the northernmost part of [[Alaska]]. He said he made the walk as a “celebration of freedom” and because he wasn't aware of anyone completing such a continuous journey along the two continents before. A few months into the project, he married Yoshiko Matsumoto of Japan in Argentina, and she accompanied him on part of the way. She returned to Japan twice to have their children, and the family traveled to be with him for the final leg.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://people.com/archive/19000-miles-later-george-meegan-says-his-way-is-no-longer-the-highway-vol-20-no-15|title=19,000 Miles Later, George Meegan Says His Way Is No Longer the Highway|author=Susan Reed|magazine=People|date=October 10, 1983|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/09/18/British-adventurer-George-Meegan-completes-19021-mile-six-year-walk/4766432705600|title=British adventurer George Meegan completes 19,021-mile, six-year walk|publisher=UPI|date=September 18, 1983|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>

===Konstantin Rengarten===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|16,700|mi}}
* '''Date:''' August 1894-September 1898
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|341|mi}}
* '''Details:''' The highly educated Russian spent a decade preparing for what some believe was the first true walk around the world. Starting from Riga, he paid his own way and didn't claim to be lured by a bet or dare, as some world walkers did. His route included South Russia, Iran, Armenia, Siberia, Mongolia, Japan, the US, France and Germany. He wrote regular reports to newspapers and didn't change his story.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ultrarunninghistory.com/around-the-world-3|title=Around the World on Foot (1984–1899)|author=Davy Crockett|publisher=Ultrarunning History|date=November 26, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== Steven Newman ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|15,509|mi}}
* '''Date:''' April 1983-April 1987
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|323|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Journalist [[Steven M. Newman]] crossed 21 countries on a four-year solo walk. His motive was a “deep urge to find out if (the world) was really such a terrible place as everybody was saying.” He concluded that it wasn't, even though he was arrested several times, attacked by bandits and a drunken construction worker, and had to fend off wild boars and other creatures.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://people.com/archive/world-girdler-steve-newman-sets-a-record-by-walking-in-a-very-very-big-circle-vol-27-no-13|title=World-Girdler Steve Newman Sets a Record by Walking in a Very, Very Big Circle|author=Roger Wolmuth|date=March 30, 1987|magazine=People|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2010/03/08/east-fork-state-park-in-ohio-has-trail-named-for-famed-world-hiker|title=East Fork State Park in Ohio has trail named for famed world hiker|date=March 8, 2010|newspaper=Denver Post|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== David Kunst ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|14,450|mi}}
* '''Date:''' June 1970-October 1974
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|278|mi}}
* '''Details:''' With a mule and hero send-off, brothers John and [[David Kunst]] started walking from Minnesota to New York and then through Europe, with a goal of completing the first verified walk around the Earth. They also raised funds for [[UNICEF]], although some questioned whether that had a pure motive.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ultrarunninghistory.com/dave-kunst-1 |title=Dave Kunst – Walk Around the World|author=Davy Crockett|publisher=Ultrarunning History|date=January 17, 2020|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref> In Afghanistan, they were attacked by bandits, and John was shot and killed. David was also shot but survived by acting like he was dead. After returning to Minnesota for a few months to recuperate, David continued with another brother, Peter, from the point where John had died. They were denied access to the Soviet Union and China, and southeast Asia was wracked with war. So they flew from India to Australia. Peter left the project after developing leg problems, so David walked alone with a mule, which died, causing him to have to push supplies with a cart. An Australian teacher aided him, and he later married her, even though he had three children with a Minnesota woman who supported his walk.<ref>Ibid.</ref> [[Guinness World Records]] cited his accomplishment as the “first verified achievement” of circumnavigating the planet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/first-circumnavigation-by-walking|title=First circumnavigation by walking|publisher=Guinness World Records|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== Prem Kumar ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|10,500|mi}}
* '''Date:''' October 1982-August 1986
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|228|mi}}
* '''Details:''' As founder of social service organizations in India, Prem Kumar walked to raise awareness for peace and development in poorer countries. He then organised walks in India involving participants from other countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/bound-by-walk-for-friendship-and-peace/articleshow/57300983.cms|title=Bound by walk for friendship and peace|newspaper=The Times of India|date=February 23, 2017|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== Louis Michael Figueroa ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|7,500|mi}}
* '''Date:''' January 2005-June 2005, June 2010-January 2011
* '''Miles walked per month:''' {{convert|536|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Walking for victims of child abuse in January 2005, Figueroa was forced to stop after six months due to legal issues and complications from leukemia. He started again in 2010 and finished the circumference route around the US in Tucson, Arizona. In 1982, Figueroa ran across the country in just 60 days to raise funds for cancer victims. He walked across the country to raise funds for AIDS victims in 1996.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thevintagenews.com/2018/10/05/forrrest-gump-run|title=Forrest Gump's Iconic Run Across the Country was Inspired by a Real Life Hero|author=Ian Harvey|publisher=The Vintage News|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>

==Longest Runs, Wheelchair Expeditions ==

=== Tony Mangan ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|31,069|mi}}
* '''Date:''' October 2010-October 2014
* '''Miles run per month:''' {{convert|647|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Beginning in his native Ireland, distance runner [[Tony Mangan]] jogged through North America, Central and South America, Australia, Asia and Europe, raising funds for a charity that battled depression. He ran with a stroller named Nirvana, which carried a tent, clothes, food, and other belongings. .<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/life/health-wellbeing/tony-mangan-returns-from-running-the-world-30600491.html|title=Tony Mangan returns from running the world|publisher=Dublin Independent|author=Frank Greally|date=September 19, 2014|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== Robert Garside ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|29,826|mi}}
* '''Date:''' October 1997-June 2003
* '''Miles run per month:''' {{convert|439|mi}}
* '''Details:''' British runner [[Robert Garside]] was cited by [[Guinness World Records]] as being the first person to run around the world. He started in India and jogged through Tibet, China, Japan, Australia, South America, Mexico, the US, Africa, Turkey and back to India. He had considerable corporate sponsors and met his future wife in Venezuela. He got mugged twice at gunpoint and was jailed in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/mar/28/travel.travelnews|title=Running the world or a flight of fancy?|newspaper=The Guardian|author=Oliver Burkeman|date=March 27, 2007|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

=== Rick Hansen ===
* '''Length:''' {{convert|24,900|mi}}
* '''Date:''' March 1985-May 1987
* '''Miles wheeled per month:''' {{convert|958|mi}}
* '''Details:''' Canadian wheelchair athlete [[Rick Hansen]] pushed his way through 34 countries on four continents. He wheeled on the [[Great Wall of China]] and met [[Pope John Paul II]] at the [[Vatican City|Vatican]]. He wore out 160 tires and was robbed four times. The project raised $26 million for spinal cord injury research.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/archives/entry/1987-rick-hansen-completes-his-man-in-motion-tour|title=Rick Hansen completes his Man in Motion tour|publisher=CBC|author=Jane Chalmers|date=May 22, 1987|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>

