{{about|the indoor sports facility|the fitness club|health club|the school class known as "gym"|physical education| the type of school|Gymnasium (school)|other uses|gymnasium (disambiguation)}} {{short description|Building designed and equipped for athletics and fitness}} {{Globalize|date=December 2008}} [[File:Amsterdam - Gymnasium - 0591.jpg|thumb|Inside a gymnasium in Amsterdam]]
A '''gymnasium''', also known as a '''gym''', is a covered location for [[Athletics (physical culture)|athletics]]. The word is derived from the [[ancient Greek]] [[Gymnasium (ancient Greece)|''gymnasium'']].<ref>{{harvnb|Partridge|1984|p=517}}</ref> They are commonly found in athletic and [[Physical fitness|fitness]] centers, and as activity and [[learning space]]s in educational institutions. "Gym" is also slang for "[[fitness center]]", which is often an area for indoor recreation. A gym may be open air as well. A gym is a place with a number of [[Equipment|equipments]] and [[Machine|machines]] used by the people to do exercises.
==Overview== [[File:Gville UF Florida Gym01.jpg|thumb|The [[Florida Gymnasium]] at the [[University of Florida]]]] [[File:TWU Gymnastics (Floor) Floor Warm Up (5694074973).jpg|thumb|Students of [[Texas Woman's University]] practicing in their university gymnasium, 2011]] [[File:Varpaisjärven liikuntahalli - Kirjastontie 4, Varpaisjärvi - Lapinlahti.jpg|thumb|The Varpaisjärvi Sports Hall in [[Lapinlahti]], [[Finland]]]] Gymnasia apparatuses such as barbells, jumping board, running path, tennis-balls, cricket field, and fencing area are used as exercises. In safe weather, outdoor locations are the most conducive to health.<ref>{{harvnb|Ravenstein|Hulley|1867}}</ref> Gyms were popular in ancient Greece. Their curricula included self-defense, gymnastica medica, or physical therapy to help the sick and injured, and for physical fitness and sports, from boxing to dancing to skipping rope.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=627}}</ref>
Gymnasia also had teachers of wisdom and philosophy. Community gymnastic events were done as part of the celebrations during various village festivals. In ancient Greece there was a phrase of contempt, "He can neither swim nor write." After a while, however, Olympic athletes began training in buildings specifically designed for them.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Editors|first=History com|title=The Olympic Games|url=https://www.history.com/topics/sports/olympic-games|access-date=2020-09-30|website=HISTORY|language=en}}</ref> Community sports never became as popular among ancient Romans as it had among the [[ancient Greece|ancient Greeks]]. Gyms were used more as a preparation for military service or spectator sports. During the [[Roman Empire]], the gymnastic art was forgotten. In the [[Dark Ages (historiography)|Dark Ages]] there were sword fighting tournaments and of [[chivalry]]; and after [[gunpowder]] was invented sword fighting began to be replaced by the sport of [[fencing]], as well as schools of dagger fighting and wrestling and boxing.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=628}}</ref>
In the 18th century, Salzmann, German clergyman, opened a gym in Thuringia teaching bodily exercises, including running and swimming. Clias and Volker established gyms in London, and in 1825, Doctor Beck, a German immigrant, established the first gymnasium in the United States. It was found that gym pupils lose interest in doing the same exercises, partly because of age. Variety in exercises included skating, dancing, and swimming. Some gym activities can be done by 6 to 8-year-olds while age 16 has been considered mature enough for boxing and horseback riding.<ref>{{harvnb|Partington|1838|p=629}}</ref>
In [[Ancient Greece]], the ''[[Gymnasium (ancient Greece)|gymnasion]]'' (γυμνάσιον) was a locality for both physical and intellectual [[education]] of young men. The latter meaning of intellectual education persisted in [[Greek language|Greek]], [[German language|German]] and other languages to denote a certain type of school providing [[secondary education]], the [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]], whereas in [[English language|English]] the meaning of physical education pertained in the word 'gym'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gymnasium (Greek) |url=https://www.ancient.eu/Gymnasium/ |website=Ancient Encyclopedia |access-date=1 April 2019}}</ref> The Greek word ''gymnasium'', which means "school for naked exercise," was used to designate a locality for the [[education]] of young men, including physical education (''[[gymnastics]]'', for example, exercise) which was customarily performed naked, as well as [[bathing]], and studies. For the Greeks, physical education was considered as important as cognitive learning. Most Greek ''gymnasia'' had libraries that for use after relaxing in the baths.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}
== History == [[File:Children's outdoor gymnasium circa 19th Century.jpg|thumb|400px|Children's outdoor gymnasium, circa 19th Century. The equipment, which was standard for the time, includes ladders, gymnastic horses, and parallel bars.]] The first recorded gymnasiums date back to over 3000 years ago in ancient [[Persia]], where they were known as ''[[Pahlevani and zoorkhaneh rituals|zurkhaneh]]'', areas that encouraged physical fitness. The larger [[Thermae|Roman Baths]] often had attached fitness facilities, the baths themselves sometimes being decorated with [[mosaic]]s of local champions of sport. Gyms in [[Germany]] were an outgrowth of the ''Turnplatz'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-turnplatz-open-air-gymnasium-in-the-hasenheide-1811-48390278.html |title=Stock Photo – Turnplatz (open-air gymnasium) in the Hasenheide, 1811 |last=Limited |first=Alamy |website=Alamy |language=en |access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> an outdoor space for gymnastics founded by German educator [[Friedrich Jahn]] in 1811<ref>{{cite book |last=Goodbody |first=John |title=The Illustrated History of Gymnastics |url=https://archive.org/details/illustratedhisto0000good |url-access=registration |publisher=Stanley Paul & Co. |location=London |year=1982 |isbn=0-09-143350-9}}</ref> and later promoted by the [[Turners]], a nineteenth-century political and gymnastic movement. The first American to open a public gym in the United States using Jahn's model was [[John Neal (writer)|John Neal]] of [[Portland, Maine]] in 1827.<ref>{{cite book | last = Leonard | first = Fred Eugene | title = A Guide to the History of Physical Education | publisher = Lea & Febiger | location = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania and New York, New York | year = 1923 | url = https://archive.org/details/guidetohistoryof00leon/ | pages = 227–250}}</ref> The first indoor gymnasium in Germany was probably the one built in [[Hesse]] in 1852 by Adolph Spiess.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HZy2BgAAQBAJ&q=first+indoor+gymnasium+in+germany&pg=PT9 |title=INTRODUCTION TO PHYSICAL EDUCATION |last=Dalvi |first=Rajani |isbn=9781312161344 |access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>
Through worldwide colonization, Great Britain expanded its national interest in sports and games to many countries. In the 1800s, programs were added to schools and college curricula that emphasized health, strength, and bodily measure. Sports drawn from European and British cultures thrived as college students and upper-class clubs financed competition. As a result, towns began building playgrounds that furthered interest in sports and physical activity.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Introduction to physical education, exercise science, and sport studies |last=Lumpkin |first=Angela |publisher=McGraw-Hill Education; 9 edition |date=January 29, 2013 |isbn=978-0-07-802266-1 |page=226 }}</ref> In the [[United States]], the Turner movement thrived in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. The first Turners group was formed in London in 1848. The Turners built gymnasia in several cities like Cincinnati and [[St. Louis]] which had large [[German American]] populations. These gyms were utilized by adults and youth. For example, a young [[Lou Gehrig]] would frequent the Turner gym in [[New York City]] with his father. [[File:ErfgoedLeiden LEI001015553 Gymnastiekzaal van de Gymnastiekschool aan de Pieterskerkgracht in Leiden.jpeg|thumb|220x220px|Interior of a gym in The Netherlands, around 1900]] The [[Boston Young Men's Christian Union]] claims to be "America's First Gym". The [[YMCA]] first organized in [[Boston]] in 1851 and a smaller branch opened in Rangasville in 1852.<ref name="Mouheb 2012 p. 177">{{cite book |last=Mouheb |first=R.B. |title=Yale Under God |publisher=Xulon Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-61996-884-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8V_Hws1hbXEC&pg=PA177 |language=it |access-date=April 1, 2019 |page=177}}</ref> Ten years later there were some two hundred YMCAs across the country, most of which provided gymnasia for exercise, games, and social interaction.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}
The 1920s was a decade of prosperity that witnessed the building of large numbers of public high schools with a gymnasium, an idea founded by Nicolas Isaranga.].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}
Today, gymnasia are commonplace in the United States. They are in virtually all U.S. [[colleges]] and [[high school]]s, as well as almost all [[middle school]]s and [[elementary school]]s. These facilities are used for [[physical education]], [[intramural sports]], and school gatherings. The number of gyms in the U.S. has more than doubled since the late 1980s.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=The Scope of the U.S. Health Club Industry (industry estimates). |journal=International Health, Racquet and Sportsclub Association (IHRSA). 2003. }}</ref> {{clear}}
